{"title_page": "Durants School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Durants School\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.664|-0.046|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   = \n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Special school]],<br /> [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = \n| head          = Rachel Carli\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = \n| address        = Pitfield Way\n| city          = Enfield\n| county        = [[Middlesex]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = EN3 5BY\n| local_authority           = [[London Borough of Enfield]]\n| ofsted        = yes\n| urn           = 102066\n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = 95\n| gender        = [[Coeducational]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 19\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Durants School''' is a [[coeducation]]al [[Special School]] in [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield, London]]. There are 95 pupils on the roll, between the ages of 11 and 19.\n\nAs part of a global citizenship initiative, it has a link to Dworzulu School in [[Accra]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bovair |first1=Keith |last2=Griffith |first2=Robin |title=Global citizenship: from concept to classroom |journal=Support for Learning |date=8 July 2003 |volume=18 |issue=3 |pages=107\u2013111 |doi=10.1111/1467-9604.00291 }}</ref>\n\nAn emotional awareness project, which is relatively unusual for special schools, was conducted at the school in 1996.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=Frances |last2=Wright |first2=Jonathan |title=Developing an emotional awareness programme for pupils with moderate learning difficulties at Durants School |journal=Emotional and Behavioural Difficulties |date=January 2001 |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013199 |doi=10.1080/13632750100507667 }}</ref>\n\nA unit for autistic learners was opened in 2005.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = Durants School Inspection Report\n  | publisher = ofsted\n  | date = 2005-10-05\n  | url = http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/reports/pdf/?inspectionNumber=276648&providerCategoryID=65536&fileName=\\\\school\\\\102\\\\s5_102066_20060222.pdf\n  | accessdate =2008-03-24 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Schools in Enfield}}\n\n[[Category:Special schools in the London Borough of Enfield]]\n[[Category:Community schools in the London Borough of Enfield]]\n\n\n{{London-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Durants School\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.664|-0.046|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   = \n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Special school]],<br /> [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = \n| head          = Peter De Rosa\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = \n| address        = Pitfield Way\n| city          = Enfield\n| county        = [[Middlesex]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = EN3 5BY\n| local_authority           = [[London Borough of Enfield]]\n| ofsted        = yes\n| urn           = 102066\n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = 95\n| gender        = [[Coeducational]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 19\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Durants School''' is a [[coeducation]]al [[Special School]] in [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield, London]]. There are 95 pupils on the roll, between the ages of 11 and 19.\n\nAs part of a global citizenship initiative, it has a link to Dworzulu School in [[Accra]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bovair |first1=Keith |last2=Griffith |first2=Robin |title=Global citizenship: from concept to classroom |journal=Support for Learning |date=8 July 2003 |volume=18 |issue=3 |pages=107\u2013111 |doi=10.1111/1467-9604.00291 }}</ref>\n\nAn emotional awareness project, which is relatively unusual for special schools, was conducted at the school in 1996.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=Frances |last2=Wright |first2=Jonathan |title=Developing an emotional awareness programme for pupils with moderate learning difficulties at Durants School |journal=Emotional and Behavioural Difficulties |date=January 2001 |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013199 |doi=10.1080/13632750100507667 }}</ref>\n\nA unit for autistic learners was opened in 2005.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = Durants School Inspection Report\n  | publisher = ofsted\n  | date = 2005-10-05\n  | url = http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/reports/pdf/?inspectionNumber=276648&providerCategoryID=65536&fileName=\\\\school\\\\102\\\\s5_102066_20060222.pdf\n  | accessdate =2008-03-24 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Schools in Enfield}}\n\n[[Category:Special schools in the London Borough of Enfield]]\n[[Category:Community schools in the London Borough of Enfield]]\n\n\n{{London-school-stub}}\n", "name_user": "85.255.234.108", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Durants_School"}
{"title_page": "2000 Insight.com Bowl", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA football yearly game\n| Game Name          = Insight.com Bowl\n| Optional Subheader = \n| Title Sponsor      = \n| Image              = <!-- Commented out: [[file:InsightBowlLogo.png|150px]] -->\n| Caption            = \n| Date Game Played   = December 28\n| Year Game Played   = 2000\n| Football Season    = 2000\n| Stadium            = [[Bank One Ballpark]]\n| City               = [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n| Visitor School     = University of Pittsburgh\n| Visitor Name Short = Pittsburgh\n| Visitor Nickname   = Panthers\n| Visitor Record     = 7&ndash;4  <!-- Record prior to game -->\n| Visitor AP         = \n| Visitor Coaches    = \n| Visitor BCS        = \n| Visitor Coach      = [[Walt Harris (coach)|Walt Harris]]\n| Visitor Conference = [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]]\n| Visitor1           = 7\n| Visitor2           = 0\n| Visitor3           = 13\n| Visitor4           = 9\n| Home School        = Iowa State University\n| Home Name Short    = Iowa State\n| Home Nickname      = Cyclones \n| Home Record        = 8&ndash;3  <!-- Record prior to game -->\n| Home AP            = \n| Home Coaches       = \n| Home BCS           = \n| Home Coach         = [[Dan McCarney]]\n| Home Conference    = [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]]\n| Home1              = 7\n| Home2              = 20\n| Home3              = 0\n| Home4              = 10\n| MVP                = \n| Odds               = \n| Anthem             = \n| Referee            =\n| Halftime           = \n| Attendance         = 41,813\n| Payout             = \n| US Network         = [[ESPN]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Steve Levy]]<br>[[Todd Christensen]]<br>[[Heather Cox]]\n| Ratings            = \n| Intl Network       = \n| Intl Announcers    =\n}}\n\nThe '''2000 Insight.com Bowl''' was the 12th edition of the bowl game. It featured the [[2000 Iowa State Cyclones football team|Iowa State Cyclones]] and the [[2000 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh Panthers]].\n\nPitt scored first on a 72-yard touchdown pass from [[John Turman]] to [[Antonio Bryant]], taking an early 7\u20130 lead. Iowa State answered with a 23-yard pass from [[Sage Rosenfels]] to [[Chris Anthony (American football)|Chris Anthony]], tying the game at 7, at the end of the 1st quarter.\n\nIn the second quarter, Joe Woodley scored on a 1-yard touchdown run for ISU making it 13\u20137. [[Ennis Haywood]] added a 3-yard touchdown run making it 20-7. Sage Rosenfels threw his second touchdown pass of the game, a 9 yarder to [[Chris Anthony (American football)|Chris Anthony]], as Iowa State made it 27\u20137 at halftime.\n\nIn the third quarter, Pitt quarterback [[Rod Rutherford]] scored on a 2-yard touchdown run, making it 27\u201314. John Turman later threw a 44-yard touchdown pass to Antonio Bryant making it 27\u201320.\n\nIn the fourth quarter, Iowa State's JaMaine Billups scored on a 72-yard punt return, bringing Iowa State to 34\u201320. Pitt's Nick Lotz kicked a 25-yard field goal, cutting the deficit to 34\u201323. [[Kevan Barlow]] scored on a 3-yard touchdown run, but the 2-point conversion attempt failed, leaving the score at 34\u201329. Iowa State's Carl Gomez kicked a 41-yard field goal to cap the scoring at 37\u201329.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores100/100363/100363388.htm |title=Pittsburgh vs. Iowa State |website=usatoday.com |date=December 28, 2000}}</ref>\n\nSage Rosenfels and Reggie Hayward got the MVPs. This was Iowa State's first bowl victory in school history after four previous losses.\n\n==Scoring summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Scoring Play\n! Score\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| '''1st Quarter'''\n|-\n| PIT \u2014 John Turman 72-yard pass to Antonio Bryant (Nick Lotz kick), 6:39\n| PIT 7-0\n|-\n| ISU \u2014 Sage Rosenfels 23-yard pass to Chris Anthony (Carl Gomez kick), 10:08\n| TIE 7-7\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| '''2nd Quarter'''\n|-\n| ISU \u2014 Joe Woodley 1-y