{"title_page": "Madvillainy", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Madvillainy\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Madvillain]]\n| cover      = Madvillainy cover.png\n| alt        = Grayscale photo of Doom's face behind his metal mask, with word \"MADVILLAIN\" in pixelated black font at the top left corner and small orange square at the top right corner.\n| released   = March 23, 2004\n| recorded   = 2002\u20132004\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Bionic<br><small>([[Los Angeles, California]])</small> <br/>The Bomb Shelter<br><small>([[Glendale, California]])</small> <br/>Doom's Crib<br><small>([[Atlanta, Georgia]])</small>\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Alternative hip hop]]\n*[[jazz rap]]\n*[[experimental hip hop]]\n*[[underground hip hop]]\n}}\n| length     = 46:08\n| label      = [[Stones Throw Records|Stones Throw]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Madlib]]\n*[[MF Doom|Doom]]\n}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Madvillainy 2|Madvillainy 2: The Madlib Remix]]\n| next_year  = 2008\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Madlib]]\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[Champion Sound]]<br />{{small|(with [[J Dilla]] as Jaylib)}}\n | prev_year  = 2003\n | title      = Madvillainy\n | year       = 2004\n | next_title = [[Stevie (album)|Stevie]]\n | next_year  = 2004\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[MF Doom|Doom]]\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[Vaudeville Villain]]\n | prev_year  = 2003\n | title      = Madvillainy\n | year       = 2004\n | next_title = [[Venomous Villain]]\n | next_year  = 2004\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Instrumental release\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Madvillainy Instrumentals.png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Instrumentals only\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Madvillainy\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Money Folder\" / \"America's Most Blunted\n | single1date = November 11, 2003\n | single2     = [[All Caps (song)|All Caps]]\" / \"Curls\n | single2date = February 2004\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Madvillainy''''' is the debut studio album by American [[hip hop music|hip hop]] duo [[Madvillain]], a group consisting of [[MF Doom]] ([[rapping|MC]]) and [[Madlib]] ([[hip hop production|producer]]). It was released on March 23, 2004 on [[Stones Throw Records]]. The album was recorded between 2002 and 2004 and was produced entirely by Madlib, with the exception of \"The Illest Villains\" which was produced by both Madlib and Doom. Madlib created most of the album's instrumentals during a trip to [[Brazil]], where the production was composed in his hotel room using minimal amounts of equipment: a [[Boss SP-303]], a [[turntable]], and a tape deck.<ref>https://www.stonesthrow.com/news/2005/05/mad-skills</ref> Fourteen months before the album was officially released, an unfinished demo of the album was stolen and leaked onto the internet. Frustrated over the leak, the duo stopped working on the album and returned to it only after they released other solo projects.\n\nWhile ''Madvillainy'' achieved only moderate commercial success, it still became one of the label's best-selling albums. The album peaked at number 179 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and attracted much attention from media outlets not usually covering [[hip hop music]], including ''[[The New Yorker]]''. ''Madvillainy'' received rave reviews from most music critics, who praised both Doom's lyricism and Madlib's production. \n\nRecently, thanks to greater accessibility enabled by online streaming services, the album has been widely accepted to be one of the greatest albums of the all-time. Some consider the collaboration, between iconic production and pure lyricism, to be a crown jewel of the genre (\"sui generis\"). The album has also appeared in various publications' lists of the best albums, including ''[[NME]]'' magazine's list of [[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|the 500 greatest albums of all time]].\n\n== Background ==\nIn 1997, after the death of his brother [[DJ Subroc]] and the rejection of [[KMD]]'s album ''[[Black Bastards]]'' by [[Elektra Records]], rapper Zev Love X returned to music as the masked rapper MF Doom.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hultkrans|first1=Andrew|title=MF Doom, \u2018Operation: Doomsday\u2019 (Metal Face)|url=http://www.spin.com/2011/04/mf-doom-operation-doomsday-metal-face/|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=17 August 2016|date=19 April 2011}}</ref> In 1999, he released his debut solo album ''[[Operation: Doomsday]]'' on [[Fondle 'Em Records]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fields|first1=Kiah|title=Today In Hip Hop History: MF Doom Releases Debut \u2018Operation: Doomsday\u2019 17 Years Ago|url=http://thesource.com/2016/04/20/today-in-hip-hop-history-mf-doom-releases-debut-operation-doomsday-17-years-ago/|website=[[The Source]]|accessdate=17 August 2016|date=20 April 2016}}</ref> According to [[Nathan Rabin]] of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', the album \"has attained mythic status; its legend has grown in proportion to its relative unavailability\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rabin|first1=Nathan|authorlink1=Nathan Rabin|title=MF Doom: Operation Doomsday: Lunchbox|url=https://www.avclub.com/review/mf-doom-ioperation-doomsday-lunchboxi-55081|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=17 August 2016|date=26 April 2011}}</ref> Soon after release of the album, in an interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', Madlib stated that he wanted to collaborate with two artists: [[J Dilla]] and Doom.<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\">{{cite web|last1=Weiss|first1=Jeff|title=Searching for Tomorrow: The Story of Madlib and Doom's Madvillainy|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/article/9478-searching-for-tomorrow-the-story-of-madlib-and-dooms-madvillainy/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, after Fondle 'Em closed, Doom disappeared. During that time, he lived between [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and the [[Kennesaw]] suburb of [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. Coincidentally, Eothen \"Egon\" Alapatt, who was the manager of Madlib's label [[Stones Throw Records]], had a friend in Kennesaw. He asked the friend to give Doom (who didn't know about Madlib and Stones Throw at the time) some instrumentals from Madlib. Three weeks later, the friend called back, telling him that Doom loved the instrumentals and wanted to work with Madlib. Soon, one of Doom's \"quasi-managers\" made an offer, asking for plane tickets to Los Angeles and $1,500. Despite the fact that label didn't have enough money after buying the tickets, they immediately agreed. According to Egon, soon after arrival, the manager went to him demanding money, while Doom visited Madlib:<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" />\n\n{{quote|The first thing his manager did was get me in my bedroom, which was also the office, and corner me about the 1,500 bucks. I realized that if she was in here, then Doom was with [Madlib], and the longer I kept up this charade with her, the longer they\u2019ll vibe and maybe it all might work out.}}\n\nEgon's plan was successful, and Doom and Madlib began working together. Soon after, Stones Throw Records managed to collect the money necessary to pay Doom and a contract to the label was signed, which was written on a paper plate.<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" />\n\n==Recording==\nDoom and Madlib started working on ''Madvillainy'' in 2002. Madlib created one hundred beats in a matter of weeks, some of which were used on ''Madvillainy'', some were used on his collaboration album with J Dilla ''[[Champion Sound]]'', while others were used for [[M.E.D. (rapper)|M.E.D.]]'s and [[Dudley Perkins (rapper)|Dudley Perkins]]' albums. Even though Stones Throw booked Doom a hotel room, he spent most of the time in Madlib's studio, based in an old bomb shelter in [[Mount Washington, Los Angeles]]. When the duo wasn't working on the album, they were spending free time together, drinking beer, eating [[Thai food]], [[smoking marijuana]],<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" /> and taking [[psychedelic mushrooms]].<ref>{{cite interview |last= Jackson|first= Otis|subject-link= Madlib|interviewer= Jeff \"Chairman\" Mao|title= Madlib Lecture|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DXkPPnVUm2E|location= [[New York City]]|date= 2016|work= [[Red Bull Music Academy]]|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> \"Figaro\" and \"Meat Grinder\" were among the songs recorded during this time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madvillain - Madvillainy 2LP|url=http://www.stonesthrow.com/news/2013/04/madvillain-madvillainy-2LP|publisher=[[Stones Throw]]|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2002, Madlib went to [[Brazil]] to participate in a [[Red Bull Music Academy]] lecture,<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> where he debuted the first music from the album by playing an unfinished version of \"America's Most Blunted\".<ref name=\"AVClub_decade_old\">{{cite web|last1=Thurm|first1=Eric|title=A decade on, Madvillainy is still a masterpiece from hip-hop\u2019s illest duo|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/decade-madvillainy-still-masterpiece-hip-hops-ille-202027|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=17 August 2016|date=11 March 2014}}</ref> Madlib also went crate digging during his time in Brazil, searching for obscure [[vinyl record]]s he could [[Sampling (music)|sample]] later, with fellow producers [[Cut Chemist]], [[DJ Babu]], and J.Rocc.<ref name=\"scratch\">{{cite magazine |first=Andrew |last=Mason |title= Mad Skills|url= https://www.stonesthrow.com/news/2005/05/mad-skills|magazine= [[Scratch (magazine)|Scratch]]|location= |publisher= |date= May 8, 2005|access-date= August 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=George|first1=Lynell|title=Hot on the beat's trail|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/jul/16/entertainment/et-brazil16|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=17 August 2016|date=16 July 2007}}</ref> According to Madlib himself, he bought multiple crates full of vinyl records, two of which he later lost.<ref name=\"scratch\" /> He used some of these records to produce beats for ''Madvillainy''. Most of the album,<ref name=\"scratch\" /> including beats for \"Strange Ways\", \"Raid\", and \"Rhinestone Cowboy\", was produced in his hotel room in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], using a portable [[phonograph|turntable]], a cassette deck, and a [[Roland SP-303|Boss SP-303]] sampler.<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" /> While Madlib was working on the album in Brazil, the unfinished demo was stolen and leaked on the internet, 14 months before its official release. Jeff Jank, Stones Throw's art director, remembers the leak in the interview with ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'':<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" />\n\n{{quote|Those were the early days of internet leaks, and we thought it would completely ruin sales. People were approaching Doom and Madlib at shows to tell them how much they liked the album, so they were like, 'Fuck it, I'm done.' Madlib started on other stuff, and Doom, well, you never know what he's doing.}}\n\nDoom and Madlib decided to work on different projects. Madlib released ''[[Champion Sound]]'' with J Dilla, while Doom released two solo albums: ''[[Take Me to Your Leader (King Geedorah album)|Take Me to Your Leader]]'', as King Geedorah, and ''[[Vaudeville Villain]]'', as Viktor Vaughn. Nevertheless, after the release of these albums, they decided to return to ''Madvillainy''. For the final version of the album, Doom altered his voice, described by [[Peanut Butter Wolf]] as going from \"really hyper, more enthusiastic\" to \"a more mellow, relaxed, confident, less abrasive\", and changed some lyrics to coincide with this change. Madlib was also asked by the label to change some instrumentals, but told them that he forgot the samples he used, in order to allow for them to remain on the album. Additionally, the label also requested the duo make a proper ending for the album, forcing them to rent a studio for the recording of \"Rhinestone Cowboy\".<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" /> The beat used, however, was produced in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2000s|url=http://uk.complex.com/music/2011/11/the-100-best-albums-of-the-2000s/56|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\n[[File:MadlibMarch2014Echo (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Madlib (''pictured in 2014''), producer of the album and half of the duo]]\n''Madvillainy'' was produced almost entirely by [[Madlib]], except the first track, which he produced in collaboration with Doom.<ref name=\"HHDX_10year\" /> On the album, Madlib incorporates his distinctive [[Hip hop production|production]] style, based on using [[Sample (music)|samples]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Today in Hip-Hop: MF Doom and Madlib Drop 'Madvillainy'|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2015/03/today-hip-hop-mf-doom-madlib-dropped-madvillainy/|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> mostly obscure, from albums recorded in different countries.<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Garrett|editor-first=Charles Hiroshi|date=2013|title=The Grove Dictionary of American Music|title-link=The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|edition=2nd|url= |location= |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=|isbn=9780195314281|quote=He is best known for his unique approach to beatmaking and remixing which includes aggregating diverse material together from far-flung musical traditions.}}</ref> Aside from sampling records by American artists,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Oliver|first1=Matt|title=Shadows Of Today: Ten Years Of 'Madvillainy'|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/features/shadows-of-today-ten-years-of-madvillainy|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> namely from [[jazz]]<ref name=\"popmatters\" /> and [[Soul music|soul]],<ref name=\"Stereogum_Turns10\" /> Madlib also used [[Music of India|Indian]] (for example, \"Shadows of Tomorrow\" samples \"Hindu Hoon Main Na Musalman Hoon\" by [[R. D. Burman]]) and [[Music of Brazil|Brazilian]] records (\"Curls\" samples \"Airport Love Theme\" by Waldir Calmon) for ''Madvillainy''.<ref name=\"AVClub_decade_old\" /> In regards to Madlib's production on the album, he stated in an interview:\n\n<blockquote>\"I did most of the Madvillain album in Brazil. Cuts like \"Raid\" I did in my hotel room in Brazil on a portable turntable, my [[Boss SP-303|303]], and a little tape deck. I recorded it on tape, came back here, put it on CD, and DOOM made a song out of it.\"<ref>https://www.stonesthrow.com/news/2005/05/mad-skills</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe album consists of 22 songs,<ref name=\"HHDX_10year\" /> most of which are short, under 3 minutes, and contain no [[Hook (music)|hooks]] or [[Refrain|choruses]].<ref name=\"AVClub_decade_old\" /><ref name=\"Stereogum_Turns10\" /> Sam Samuelson of [[AllMusic]] compared the album to a comic book, \"sometimes segued with vignettes sampled from 1940s movies and broadcasts or left-field [marijuana]-toting skits\". He also noted that some instrumentals on the album \"[seem] to be so out of time or step with a traditional hip-hop direction\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\" /> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' compared the album to a buffet, where \"Madlib and Doom are interested in throwing out ideas as fast as they have them, giving them as much attention as they need, and moving on to the next thing\".<ref name=\"AVClub_decade_old\" /> Tim O'Neil of ''[[PopMatters]]'' praised Madlib's instrumentals and said that they \"make the album a sonic feast\".<ref name=\"popmatters\" />\n\n===Lyrics===\n{{Listen\n|filename=Madvillain - Meat Grinder.ogg\n|title=\"Meat Grinder\"\n|description=A sample of \"Meat Grinder\", described by ''[[PopMatters]]'' as \"a tongue twister, with multiple contrasting internal rhymes and almost nonsensical verses jammed together in a way that ''almost'' sounds silly but doesn't\".<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|last1=O'Neil |first1=Tim |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |url=https://www.popmatters.com/review/madvillain-madvillainy/ |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=21 August 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041204185437/http://popmatters.com/music/reviews/m/madvillain-madvillainy.shtml |archivedate= 4 December 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[HipHopDX]]'' praised the instrumental, based on sample of \"Hula Rock\" by Lew Howard & The All-Stars, and called it a \"particularly sinister piece\".<ref name=\"HHDX\" />\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\nDoom's lyrics on ''Madvillainy'' are [[Free association (psychology)|free-associative]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Breihan|first1=Tom|title=New Madvillain Album in the Works|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/36936-new-madvillain-album-in-the-works/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> According to [[Stereogum]], the album \"is about using sound to craft semi-indecipherable vignettes that are situated somewhere between the real and the mythical\".<ref name=\"Stereogum_Turns10\" /> Despite originally featuring a more enthusiastic, excited [[Flow (music)|delivery]], the leak prompted Doom to go with a slower and more relaxed flow on the final version of the album. This move has been praised by various publications, including ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', which said that it was \"ultimately better-suited\" than the original.<ref name=\"Pitchfork\" />\n\nThroughout the album, Doom uses a number of [[literary device]]s, including [[Multisyllabic rhymes|multi-syllable rhymes]], [[internal rhymes]], [[alliteration]],<ref name=\"TheNewYorker\" /> [[assonance]],<ref>{{cite book |last= Edwards|first= Paul|date= 2009|title= How to Rap: The Art & Science of the Hip-Hop MC|title-link=How to Rap|url= |location= |publisher= [[Chicago Review Press]]|page= [https://archive.org/details/howtorapartscien0000edwa/page/84 84]|isbn=9781556528163}}</ref> and [[holorime]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dart|first1=Chris|title=Deconstructing the greatest rap songs of all time, syllable by syllable|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/deconstructing-greatest-rap-songs-all-time-syllabl-237104|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=24 August 2016|date=20 May 2016}}</ref> Music critics also noted extensive use of [[wordplay]]<ref name=\"AVClub_decade_old\" /> and [[double entendre]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Downing|first1=Andy|title=Doom doesn't live up to often brilliant recordings|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-12-14/features/0512130313_1_dr-doom-biz-markie-danger-doom|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=24 August 2016|date=14 December 2005}}</ref> ''PopMatters'' wrote, \"You can spend hours poring over the lyric sheet and attempting to grok Doom\u2019s infinitely dense verbiage. If language is arbitrary, then many of Doom\u2019s verses exploit the essence of words stripped of meaning, random conglomerations of syllables assembled in an order that only makes sense from a rhythmical standpoint\", the critic added.<ref name=\"popmatters\" /> ''[[The Observer]]'' stated that \"the densely telegraphic lyrics almost always reward closer inspection\" and that Doom's \"rhymes miss beats, drop into the middle of the next line, work their way through whole verses\" allows for a smooth listen.<ref name=\"TheObserver\" />\n\n==Artwork==\nThe album cover art was created by Stones Throw's art director Jeff Jank, based on a grayscale photo of Doom in his metal mask. In an interview with ''[[Ego Trip (magazine)|Ego Trip]]'', Jank said:<ref name=\"egotrip\">{{cite web|title=UNCOVERED: The Story Behind Madvillain's \"Madvillainy\" (2004) with art director Jeff Jank|url=http://www.egotripland.com/album-cover-madvillain-madvillainy-jeff-jank/|website=[[Ego Trip (magazine)|Ego Trip]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Back then, 2003, Doom didn't really have public image. Hip hop heads knew he wore a mask, that he'd been in KMD a decade earlier, but he really was a mystery. So, I really wanted to get a shot of him on the cover, just to make a definitive 'Doom cover'. Specifically, I was thinking of a picture of this man, who happened to wear a mask for some reason, as opposed to 'a picture of a mask'. I don't know if the distinction would occur to anyone else, but to me it was a big deal. I mean, who the hell goes around with a metal mask, what's his story?}}\n\nThe photo was created by photographer Eric Coleman at Stones Throw's house in Los Angeles, and edited by Jank. While working on the ''Madvillainy'' album cover, Jank drew inspiration from [[King Crimson]]'s ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]'' artwork, however, following its completion, he noticed the artwork eerily resembled [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s ''[[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna]]'' artwork. Despite this, Jank stuck with the original artwork, labeling it as the \"rap version of ''[[Beauty and the Beast]]''\". A small orange square was added to the final version of ''Madvillainy'', due to Jank's thinking that the artwork \"needed something distinctive\", comparing it to the orange \"O\" on the ''Madonna'' cover.<ref name=\"egotrip\" />\n\n==Release and promotion==\nTwo singles from ''Madvillainy'' were released before the album release: \"Money Folder\" b/w \"America's Most Blunted\", and \"All Caps\" b/w \"Curls\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Madvillain {{!}} Money Folder & Most Blunted|url=https://www.stonesthrow.com/store/12-inch/madvillain/money-folder-2|publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Madvillain {{!}} Curls & All Caps|url=https://www.stonesthrow.com/store/12-inch/madvillain/curls-all-caps|publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> The first single peaked at #66 on the Billboard [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart.<ref name=\"hot_songs\" /> ''Madvillainy'' was released on March 23, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kangas|first1=Chaz|title=March 23, 2004: The Most Important Day in Indie Rap History?|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/march-23-2004-the-most-important-day-in-indie-rap-history-6626264|website=[[Village Voice]]|accessdate=18 August 2016|date=21 March 2014}}</ref> Despite [[Stones Throw Records]] being a relatively small label, the album achieved moderate commercial success, which was big for the label. According to ''Pitchfork'', \"after two years of hectoring Stones Throw for making unsalable records, distributor [[EMI]] couldn't keep ''Madvillainy'' in stock.\"<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" /> The album peaked at number 179 on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"billboard200\" /> and sold approximately 150,000 copies,<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" /> making it one of the label's best-selling albums.<ref>{{cite book |last= Ferguson|first= Jordan|date= |title= J Dilla's Donuts|series= [[33\u2153]]|url= |location= |publisher= [[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|page= |isbn=9781623563608|quote= [...] Their album Madvillainy quickly became one of Stones Throw's highest-selling albums and most critically acclaimed.}}</ref> Its success allowed Stones Throw to open an office in [[Highland Park, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" />\n\nFour videos were filmed for the album: \"[[All Caps (song)|All Caps]]\" (directed by James Reitano), \"Rhinestone Cowboy\" and \"Accordion\" (both directed by Andrew Gura),<ref name=\"HHDX_10year\">{{cite web|last1=Balfour|first1=Jay|title=Madvillain \"Madvillainy\" In Review: 10-Year Anniversary|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.28021/title.madvillain-madvillainy-in-review-10-year-anniversary|website=[[HipHopDX]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> and \"Shadows of Tomorrow\" (directed by [[System D-128]]). \"All Caps\" and \"Rhinestone Cowboy\" appear on the [[DVD]] ''Stones Throw 101''<ref>{{cite web|title=Stones Throw {{!}} Stones Throw 101|url=https://www.stonesthrow.com/store/cd-dvd/stones-throw/stones-throw-101|publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> along with a hidden easter egg video for \"Shadows Of Tomorrow\" as a hidden feature. An impromptu video for \"Accordion\" was filmed in 2004 but was not released until 2008's ''In Living the True Gods'' DVD.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stones Throw {{!}} Stones Throw 102: In Living the True Gods|url=https://www.stonesthrow.com/store/dvd/stones-throw/stones-throw-102-in-living-the-true-gods|publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nAn [[instrumental]] version of the album was released in 2004 only in vinyl format and digitally through various online stores, with the tracks \"The Illest Villains\", \"Bistro\", \"Sickfit\", \"Do Not Fire!\", and \"Supervillain Theme\" being omitted. It was re-released in 2012 on vinyl with picture sleeve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stones Throw to release Madvillainy Instrumentals with full picture sleeve|url=http://www.factmag.com/2012/01/23/stones-throw-to-reissue-madvillainy-instrumentals/|website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, in honor of the 10th anniversary of ''Madvillainy'', Stones Throw released special edition of the album on vinyl.<ref>{{cite web|title=MADVILLAIN - MADVILLAINY|url=https://www.stonesthrow.com/news/2014/03/madvillain-madvillainy|publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> The album re-entered ''Billboard'' 200 chart, peaking at number 117,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caulfield|first1=Keith|title=Billboard 200 Chart Moves: 'Frozen' Exits Top 10 After 39 Weeks|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6258982/frozen-soundtrack-album-charts|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> higher than it did originally. The same year ''Madvillainy'' was also released on [[Compact Cassette]]s, as part of the [[Cassette Store Day]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kaye|first1=Ben|title=Cassette Store Day to return in 2014, with releases from Julian Casablancas, Karen O, and Foxygen|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/08/cassette-store-day-to-return-in-2014-with-releases-from-julian-casablancas-karen-o-and-foxygen/|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=18 August 2016|date=24 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Remixes===\nSeveral [[remix]]es of the album were released.<ref name=\"HHDX_10year\" /> Two remix EPs of ''Madvillainy'' were released on Stones Throw in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=MF Doom Discography|url=http://www.stonesthrow.com/doom/discography|publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]]|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> The remixes were done by [[Four Tet]] and [[Koushik]].<ref name=\"HHDX_10year\" /> ''[[Madvillainy 2|Madvillainy 2: The Madlib Remix]]'' was released on Stones Throw in 2008, containing a complete remix of the album by Madlib as a part of a Madvillain box set.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stonesthrow.com/news/madvillain-box |title=Madvillainy 2: The Box |publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]] |date=July 23, 2008 |accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> According to [[Stereogum]], it was Madlib's \"attempt to get Doom excited enough to work on a true follow-up\",<ref name=\"Stereogum_Turns10\">{{cite web|last1=Behrens|first1=Sam|title=Madvillainy Turns 10|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1671172/madvillainy-turns-10/franchises/the-anniversary/|website=[[Stereogum]]|accessdate=20 August 2016|date=24 March 2014}}</ref> recorded after he got tired of waiting for Doom to record the official sequel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patrin|first1=Nate|title=Madvillain: Madvillainy 2 Album Review|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12061-madvillainy-2/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 93/100<ref name=\"mc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/madvillainy/madvillain/ |title=Reviews for Madvillainy by Madvillain |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/madvillainy-mw0000335176 |title=Madvillainy \u2013 Madvillain |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=November 14, 2009 |last=Samuelson |first=Sam}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2Score = 5/5<ref name=\"AltPress\">{{cite journal |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |issue=191 |date=June 2004 |page=110}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B<ref name=\"Hermes\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2004/03/19/madvillain |title=Madvillainy |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 19, 2004 |accessdate=November 14, 2009 |last=Hermes |first=Will |authorlink=Will Hermes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804134802/https://ew.com/article/2004/03/19/madvillain/ |archivedate=August 4, 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev4Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite journal |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |issue=127 |date=June 2004 |page=114}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"TheObserver\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/observer/omm/reviews/story/0,13875,1219526,00.html |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[The Observer]] |date=May 23, 2004 |accessdate=April 29, 2016 |last=Guest |first=Tim |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601104057/http://www.theguardian.com/observer/omm/reviews/story/0,13875,1219526,00.html |archivedate=June 1, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 9.4/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/5579-madvillainy/ |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=March 25, 2004 |accessdate=November 14, 2009 |last1=Pemberton |first1=Rollie |authorlink1=Cadence Weapon |last2=Sylvester |first2=Nick}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Q\">{{cite journal |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=216 |date=July 2004 |page=116}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite journal |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=948 |date=May 13, 2004 |last=Caramanica |first=Jon |authorlink=Jon Caramanica |page=74}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Slant Magazine]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Henderson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madvillain-madvillainy |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=December 17, 2004 |accessdate=November 14, 2009 |last=Henderson |first=Eric}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv704-04.php |title=Consumer Guide: Looking Past Differences |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=August 24, 2004 |accessdate=November 14, 2009 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Madvillainy'' received rave reviews from music critics and became one of the most critically acclaimed projects of both artists.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Clarke|first1=Khari|title=Is It True?: Doom Says Madvillainy Sequel is \u2018Just About Done\u2019|url=http://thesource.com/2014/04/12/is-it-true-doom-says-madvillainy-sequel-is-just-about-done/|website=[[The Source]]|accessdate=20 August 2016|date=12 April 2014}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 93, based on 20 reviews; it was the year's best-reviewed rap album and third highest reviewed album overall, according to the website. It also was the second most acclaimed rap album at the time of its release, behind [[Outkast|Outkast's]] ''[[Stankonia]]''.<ref name=\"mc\" /> Sam Samuelson of [[AllMusic]] wrote that album's strength \"lies in its mix between seemingly obtuse beats, samples, MCing, and some straight-up hip-hop bumping\" and that \"MF Doom's unpredictable lyrical style fits quite nicely within Madlib's unconventional beat orchestrations\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\" /> [[Will Hermes]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called it \"indie rap blowing session by two guys near the top of their game\".<ref name=\"Hermes\" /> ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' praised ''Madvillainy'' as \"all invention and no indulgence\",<ref name=\"AltPress\"/> while ''[[HipHopDX]]'' dubbed it an \"experimental, eclectic, raw, spontaneous\" classic.<ref name=\"HHDX\">{{cite web|author1=J-23|title=Madvillain - Madvillainy|url=http://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.386/title.madvillain-madvillainy|website=[[HipHopDX]]|accessdate=19 August 2016|date=March 16, 2004}}</ref> ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' praised the album, calling it \"a symphony of such densely constructed chaos\" and noting that \"''Madvillainy'''s very opacity is part of its brilliance\".<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n\n''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called ''Madvillainy'' \"inexhaustibly brilliant, with layer-upon-layer of carefully considered yet immediate hip-hop, forward-thinking but always close to its roots\", noting that \"the samples are smart and never played-out, and the production and rhymes reveal a determined sense of cooperation, as MF Doom spouts off his most brilliant lyrical change-ups and production-conscious playoffs\".<ref name=\"Pitchfork\" /> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' called Madlib \"the most innovative beatsman since [[Prince Paul (producer)|Prince Paul]]\", who created \"an oddball, cartoon-heavy backdrop for MF Doom's mellifluous wordplay\".<ref name=\"Q\" /> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave ''Madvillainy'' praised Madlib's tracks, \"fuzzy and crackling with dust\", and MF Doom, whose flow is \"a particularly elegant slur, with syllables speading over a beat, not crisply adhering to it\".<ref name=\"RS\" /> Eric Henderson of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' called it \"a chameleonic masterpiece that alone validates the artistry of sampler culture\".<ref name=\"Henderson\"/> [[Robert Christgau]], writing for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', praised the album as \"a glorious phantasmagoria of flow\".<ref name=\"Christgau\" /> ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''{{'}}s [[Jody Rosen]] called it a \"torrid album that marries old-school rap aesthetics to punk-rock concision.\"<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2046.html |title=Madvillain: Madvillainy |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |issue=26 |date=May 2004 |accessdate=September 23, 2016 |last=Rosen |first=Jody |authorlink=Jody Rosen |page=127 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040818000135/http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2046.html |archivedate=August 18, 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''Madvillainy'' also attracted positive reviews from several publications with infrequent coverage of hip hop music.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fields|first1=Kiah|title=Today in Hip Hop History: Madvillain Drops Madvillainy 12 Years Ago|url=http://thesource.com/2016/03/23/today-in-hip-hop-history-madvillain-drops-madvillainy-12-years-ago/|website=[[The Source]]|accessdate=20 August 2016|date=23 March 2016}}</ref> [[David Segal (reporter)|David Segal]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called the album \"hysterical, [...] perplexing, arresting, thought-provoking or just plain silly\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Segal|first1=David|authorlink1=David Segal (reporter)|title=HERE &|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/2004/06/13/here-38/3562e43d-93a9-4169-b00c-138e3db12080/|website=[[The Washington Post]]|date=13 June 2004|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref> [[Kelefa Sanneh]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a delirious collaboration\" and hailed MF Doom as a rapper who \"understands the deformative power of rhyme\" and \"delivers long, free-associative verses full of sideways leaps and unexpected twists\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sanneh |first1=Kelefa |authorlink1=Kelefa Sanneh |title=HIP-HOP REVIEW; That Man in a Mask, With Labyrinthine Rhymes to Cast |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/07/arts/hip-hop-review-that-man-in-a-mask-with-labyrinthine-rhymes-to-cast.html?_r=0 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=20 August 2016 |date=7 April 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528023104/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/07/arts/hip-hop-review-that-man-in-a-mask-with-labyrinthine-rhymes-to-cast.html |archive-date=28 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Sasha Frere-Jones]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' praised the album, noting that \"the point of ''Madvillainy'' is largely poetic\u2014celebrating the language of music and the music of language\" and that while album's beats are based on samples of records, it's \"hard to say which ones, even in a general way\".<ref name=\"TheNewYorker\">{{cite magazine |last= Frere-Jones|first= Sasha|author-link= Sasha Frere-Jones|date= 12 April 2004|title= Doom's Day|url= https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2004/04/12/dooms-day|magazine= [[The New Yorker]]|location= |publisher= |access-date= 20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nSeveral publications included ''Madvillainy'' in their lists of the best albums of the year. ''Pitchfork'' ranked it number six on their list of the 50 best albums of 2004, stating that \"the collaboration brings out the best in both men, without copying anything in their catalogs\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 50 Albums of 2004|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/5934-top-50-albums-of-2004/?page=5|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref> ''Prefix'' ranked the album first on its list of the 60 best albums of 2004, stating that \"when Doom and Madlib combine, they form like [[Voltron]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prefixmag.com/features/the-best-albums-of-2004/a-look-back-at-the-best-albums-of-the-year/12573/|title=A look back at the best albums of the year:|website=Prefixmag|language=en|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' positioned it at number nine on their list of the 100 best albums of 2004, commending MF Doom's \"royal, pop culture-laden flow\" and Madlib's \"beat-mining expertise\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Umile |first1=Dominic |title=Best Music of 2004 |url=https://www.popmatters.com/music/best2004/index-10-6.shtml/ |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=20 August 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050109051003/http://www.popmatters.com/music/best2004/index-10-6.shtml |archivedate= 9 January 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' ranked it number 17 on their list of the 40 best albums of 2004, praising Madlib's production, \"thick, woozy slabs of beatnik bass\", that \"keeps things hotter than an underground volcano lair\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Patrin|first= Nate|date= January 2005|title= 40 Best Albums of the Year|url= http://www.spin.com/2004/12/40-best-albums-2004/madvillain-madvillainy/|magazine= [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location= |publisher= |page=66|access-date= 20 August 2016}}</ref> [[Washington City Paper]] ranked Madvillainy number one on their list of the top 20 albums of 2004. ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' named it the second best album of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pemberton|first1=Rollie|title=The Top 40 Albums of 2004|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1402|website=[[Stylus Magazine]]|accessdate=20 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050116054349/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1402|archivedate=16 January 2005}}</ref> In ''The Village Voice''{{'s}} annual poll [[Pazz & Jop]], which combined votes from 793 critics, ''Madvillainy'' was ranked number 11 on the list of the best albums of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pazz & Jop 2004|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/specials/pazznjop/04/albums_winners1.php|website=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=20 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050210035404/http://www.villagevoice.com/specials/pazznjop/04/albums_winners1.php|archivedate=10 February 2005}}</ref> ''[[The Wire]]''<ref>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |date= January 2005|issue=251|title= 2004 Rewind|url= http://www.thewire.co.uk/issues/charts/2004-rewind|magazine= [[The Wire]]|page=74|location= |publisher= |access-date= 20 August 2016}}</ref> and [[AllMusic]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Editors' Choice |url=https://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=23::4%3C~T3 |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=20 August 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050214165904/http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=23%3A%3A4%3C~T3 |archivedate=14 February 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> also included the album in their unordered lists of the best albums of the year.\n\nNumerous publications included ''Madvillainy'' in various lists of the best albums. ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]'' positioned it at number 47 in their list of top 100 albums of ''Clash''{{'s}} lifetime, calling it \"slapdash and dilapidated, wholly unconcerned with making sense\", \"defined by its flippancy and attitude to professionalism\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Oliver|first1=Matt|title=The Top 100 Albums Of Clash's Lifetime: 50-41|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/features/the-top-100-albums-of-clashs-lifetime-50-41|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> The magazine also listed it on their list of ten best hip hop albums ever, calling it \"one of this decade\u2019s finest hip-hop albums\" that \"elevated the profile of both [artists] to whole new levels\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Diver|first1=Mike|title=Top Ten - Hip-Hop Albums|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/features/top-ten-hip-hop-albums|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' placed the album in their list of 100 best albums available on [[Spotify]], calling it \"dusty, weeded up, 22-song masterpiece that stood alone and brought us all into its own little world\" and stating that \"Madlib and MF Doom's classic wasn't meant for the radio, but it was too good to be kept to the [[Underground hip hop|underground]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The 100 Best Albums Streaming On Spotify Right Now|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/04/the-100-best-albums-on-spotify/|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> The magazine also listed it among 25 albums of the decade that deserve classic status, describing it as \"a classic record that had a goofy cartoony unpredictability, balanced with moments of oddball sincerity\" and 71st on the list \"The 100 Best Albums of the Complex Decade\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/04/the-100-best-albums-of-the-complex-era/madvillain-madvillainy|title=The 100 Best Albums of The Complex Decade: 71. Madvillain, ''Madvillainy'' (2004)|last=|first=|date=|website=Complex|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ahmed|first1=Insanul|last2=Martin|first2=Andrew|last3=Isenberg|first3=Daniel|last4=Drake|first4=David|last5=Baker|first5=Ernest|last6=Moore|first6=Jacob|last7=Nostro|first7=Lauren|title=25 Rap Albums From the Past Decade That Deserve Classic Status|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/12/25-rap-albums-from-the-past-decade-that-deserve-classic-status/|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' featured the album on the list \"The Best Music of the Decade\", referring to the album as \"an instant masterpiece\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/the-best-music-of-the-decade-35540|title=The best music of the decade|date=2009-11-19|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref> ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'' ranked it number 14 at their list of 100 best albums of the 2000s and praised it as \"a perfect synergy between raw beats and incredible rhymes\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beatnick|first1=Mr.|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2000s|url=http://www.factmag.com/2010/12/01/100-best-albums-of-the-decade/9/|website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> The magazine also named it the second best album on their list of 100 best indie hip hop records ever made, stating that it was \"arguably the signature moment from the signature rapper and signature producer of the entire movement\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Piyevsky|first1=Alex|last2=Twells|first2=John|last3=Raw|first3=Son|last4=Rascobeamer|first4=Jeff|author5=Geng|title=The 100 best indie hip-hop records of all time|url=http://www.factmag.com/2015/02/25/the-100-best-indie-hip-hop-records-of-all-time/100/|website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=25 February 2015|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> [[Heavy.com]] ranked the album number 9 on their list \"The Top 10 Hip-Hop Albums of the Decade\", stating that \"MF Doom has never sounded better than he did when he teamed up with Madlib for this little ditty of WTF hip hop\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://heavy.com/music/2009/12/top-10-hip-hop-albums-of-the-decade/|title=Top 10 Hip-Hop Albums Of The Decade|last=Hughes|first=Terrance|date=2009-12-22|newspaper=Heavy.com|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-18}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' placed the album at number 39 on the list \"The 100 Best Albums of the Aughts\", calling it the \"undisputed pinnacle of aughts underground rap\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/best-of-the-aughts-albums/P13|title=The 100 Best Albums of the Aughts {{!}} Feature  {{!}} Slant Magazine|newspaper=Slant Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-11}}</ref> ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' ranked the album number 13 on its list \"The Top 50 Albums: 2000-2004\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/weekly_article/the-top-50-albums-2000-2005.htm|title=The Top 50 Albums: 2000-2005 - Article - Stylus Magazine|website=www.stylusmagazine.com|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref> ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'' ranked the album 14th on its \"The 100 Best Albums of the 2000s\" list, praising it as \"a perfect synergy between raw beats and incredible rhymes that in the minds and hearts of many, neither party has yet to surpass\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2010/12/01/100-best-albums-of-the-decade/|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2000s|website=FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music.|access-date=2017-01-11}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' included the album in their list of 1000 albums to hear before you die, describing it as \"a colourful window into Dumile's world\", while praising its \"busy unpredictability and stoned comic-book mythos\".<ref>{{cite web|title=1000 albums to hear before you die|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/nov/20/1000tohearbeforeyoudie5|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=21 August 2016|date=20 November 2007}}</ref> ''[[HipHopDX]]'' included the album in two lists: top 10 albums of 2000s<ref>{{cite web|title=HipHopDX's Top 10 Albums Of The '00s|url=http://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.1459/title.hiphopdxs-top-10-albums-of-the-00s|website=[[HipHopDX]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> and the 30 best underground hip hop albums since 2000, describing it as \"the super rap album, reaching unforeseen creative heights\" that \"elevated [Doom and Madlib] into Gods for many core Hip Hop heads\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The 30 Best Underground Hip Hop Albums Since 2000|url=http://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.2991/title.the-30-best-underground-hip-hop-albums-since-2000|website=[[HipHopDX]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' featured it on their list of 40 one album wonders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/30-greatest-one-album-wonders-20160714/10-madvillain-madvillainy-2004|title=40 Greatest One-Album Wonders|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2016-12-05}}</ref>\n\n''[[NME]]'' ranked the album number 411 on their list of [[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|the 500 greatest albums of all time]], describing it as \"stoner humour and mind-bending beats from a hip-hop dream team\" and stating that \"MF Doom and Madlib might not have invented underground rap, but they damn well perfected it\".<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|url= https://www.nme.com/photos/the-500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-500-401/323975|magazine= [[NME]]|location= |publisher= |date= 23 October 2013|access-date= 21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'' ranked the album at number 13 in their list of the top 100 albums of 2000\u20132004, commenting, \"While Madlib's special power played tricks on your ears \u2013 a sample you were sure was the sound of cars rolling by on the street might sound like the hiss of a record on a different day (\"Rainbows\") \u2013 MF Doom unfurled his clever lyrics like a roll of sod on earth... and the album curved in on itself like a two-way mirror.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/5956-the-top-100-albums-of-2000-04-part-one/?page=9 |title=Staff Lists: The Top 100 Albums of 2000-04|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=7 February 2005 |accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>''Pitchfork'' also ranked ''Madvillainy'' as the 25th best album of the 2000s, describing it as \"a preternaturally perfect pairing of like-minded talents\" who \"have each been responsible for tons of great, grimy underground hip-hop\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7709-the-top-200-albums-of-the-2000s-50-21/3/ |title=Staff Lists: The Top 200 Albums of the 2000s: 50-21 &#124; Features |website=Pitchfork |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2012-02-29}}</ref> ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]'' considered the album the fourth best of the 2000s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/favorite-100-albums-2000-2009-20-01|title=Favorite 100 Albums of 2000-2009: 20-01|work=Tiny Mix Tapes|access-date=2017-07-09|language=en}}</ref> [[Rhapsody (service)|Rhapsody]] named the ranked the album 1st on its \"Hip-Hop's Best Albums of the Decade\" list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.rhapsody.com/2009/10/hiphopdecade.html |title=Hip-Hop's Best Albums of the Decade - Rhapsody: The Mix |date=2012-09-24 |access-date=2017-03-11 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120924071122/http://blog.rhapsody.com/2009/10/hiphopdecade.html |archivedate=2012-09-24 }}</ref> ''PopMatters'' positioned it at number 49 on their list of the 100 best albums of the 2000s and praised MF Doom, who \"free-associates culture high and low, from [[Ernest Hemingway|Hemingway]] to [[Robh Ruppel]], across tongue-tied internal rhymes\", and Madlib's \"fusion breaks, psych soul, and [[Steve Reich]]\", and called the album \"the best chemistry of either\u2019s career, and one of the best of hip-hop, period\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aspray|first1=Benjamin|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2000s: 60-41|url=https://www.popmatters.com/feature/186482-the-100-best-albums-of-the-00s-60-41/P2/|website=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> In 2016 ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' listed ''Madvillainy'' among the albums that didn't appear in their list of the best albums of last 30 years, stating that \"underground hip-hop's cracked geniuses, Madlib and MF Doom, unite on a labyrinth of weed-stained vignettes that combine invention and accessibility\".<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= A Q Celebration... 476 Modern Classics|url= |magazine= [[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location= |publisher= |date= June 2016|issue= 361|page=67 |access-date= }}</ref> ''Spin'' ranked it number 123 on their list of the 300 best albums of the past 30 years (1985\u20132014), calling it \"a genius cross-pollination of seemingly divergent styles\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jenkins|first1=Craig|title=The 300 Best Albums Of The Past 30 Years (1985-2014)|url=http://www.spin.com/2015/05/the-300-best-albums-of-the-past-30-years-1985-2014/3/|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=21 August 2016|date=11 May 2015}}</ref> The magazine also positioned the album at number eight on the list of the 50 best hip hop debut albums since ''[[Reasonable Doubt (album)|Reasonable Doubt]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Unterberger|first1=Andrew|title=The 50 Best Hip-Hop Debut Albums Since \u2018Reasonable Doubt\u2019|url=http://www.spin.com/featured/50-best-hip-hop-debut-albums-since-reasonable-doubt-jay-z/|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=21 August 2016|date=1 July 2016}}</ref> ''Stylus Magazine'' ranked the album number 13 on their list of the top 50 albums of 2000\u20132005, praising Madlib's production, based on \"an endless supply of funk, soul, and jazz samples\", and stating that the album was \"displaying the future of hip-hop\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cober-Lake|first1=Justin|title=The Top 50 Albums: 2000-2005|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1430|website=[[Stylus Magazine]]|accessdate=21 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050306095656/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1430|archivedate=6 March 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy and influence==\n[[File:MF Doom Mural Little Haiti.jpg|200px|thumb|[[Graffiti]] of Doom from ''Madvillainy'' cover in [[Little Haiti, Miami, Florida]]]]\n\n''Madvillainy'' influenced a generation of artists.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bassil|first1=Ryan|title=Ten Shit Hot Albums by Artists Who Only Ever Made One|url=http://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/blog/shit-hot-albums-by-artists-that-only-did-one|website=[[Noisey]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Steiner|first1=B.J.|title=Happy Birthday, Madlib!|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/10/happy-birthday-madlib/|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> Among some of them are rappers [[Joey Badass]], the late [[Capital Steez|Capital STEEZ]], [[Bishop Nehru]], [[Tyler, The Creator]], [[Earl Sweatshirt]],<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" /> [[Danny Brown (rapper)|Danny Brown]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nostro|first1=Lauren|title=Danny Brown's 25 Favorite Albums|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/10/danny-brown-favorite-albums/madvillainy|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> [[Kirk Knight]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Josephs|first1=Brian|title=Kirk Knight Is Ready to Captain This Starship|url=http://noisey.vice.com/en_ca/blog/kirk-knight-late-knight-special-interview-2015|website=[[Noisey]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> producer and rapper [[Flying Lotus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2012|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/12/2012-year-in-review-the-50-best-albums-of-2012/captain-murphy-duality|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> producer and DJ [[Cashmere Cat]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phili|first1=Stelios|title=Cashmere Cat on 10 Songs That Blow His Mind|url=https://www.gq.com/story/cashmere-cat-on-10-songs-that-blow-his-mind|website=[[GQ]]|accessdate=24 August 2016|date=11 March 2015}}</ref> [[neo soul]] collective [[Jungle (band)|Jungle]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Errol|title=The Really Wild Show: Jungle Interviewed|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/features/the-really-wild-show-jungle-interviewed|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> [[indie rock]] band [[Cults (band)|Cults]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grisham|first1=Tyler|title=Cults|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/guest-lists/8005-cults/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> and [[Radiohead]] singer [[Thom Yorke]].<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Colothan|first1=Scott|title=Thom Yorke Lists His Favourite New Sounds|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/27134/Thom-Yorke-Lists-His-Favourite-New-Sounds|website=[[Gigwise]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> According to Earl Sweatshirt, ''Madvillainy'' influenced his generation the same way [[Wu-Tang Clan]] influenced the rappers of the 1990s with their album ''[[Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers)]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weiss|first1=Jeff|title=Earl Sweatshirt, Captain Murphy and the Enduring Influence of the Madvillain|url=http://www.passionweiss.com/2012/11/07/earl-sweatshirt-captain-murphy-and-the-enduring-influence-of-the-madvillain/|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> In 2009 a video of [[Mos Def]] working on his album ''[[The Ecstatic]]'' in a studio was released. In the video he praised Doom, saying that \"he rhymes as weird as I feel\", and recited some of Doom's lines, including the ones from ''Madvillainy''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ortiz|first1=Edwin|title=Mos Def Praises MF Doom, Compares Against Lil Wayne|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.8819/title.mos-def-praises-mf-doom-compares-against-lil-wayne|website=[[HipHopDX]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> He added:<ref name=\"searching_for_tomorrow\" />\n\n{{quote|Dude, I swear to God, when I saw that Madvillain record, I bought it on vinyl. I ain't have a record player. I bought it on vinyl just to stare at the album. I stared at it and I just kept going, 'I understand you'.}}\n\nIn 2015, in honor of the release of [[All-New, All-Different Marvel]] comics line and to pay homage to classic and contemporary hip hop albums, [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] released [[variant covers]] inspired by these albums.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Towers|first1=Andrea|title=See the newest additions to Marvel's hip-hop variant covers|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/09/18/marvels-hip-hop-variant-covers-exclusive|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Minsker|first1=Evan|title=Marvel Comics Pay Homage to Hip-Hop Albums With Variant Covers|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/60386-marvel-comics-pay-homage-to-hip-hop-albums-with-variant-covers/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> One of them was variant cover of [[Jane Foster (comics)|The Mighty Thor]] comics, based on ''Madvillainy'' cover. It used grayscale image of Jane Foster's face behind the metal mask, with a picture of [[Mjolnir (comics)|Mjolnir]] in a small orange square on top right corner and \"THE MIGHTY THOR\" text in pixelated font on top left.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lynch|first1=Joe|title=Marvel Debuts Lil B, MF Doom & GZA Inspired Comic Covers: Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6649225/marvel-comics-lil-b-mf-doom-gza-exclusive|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks written by [[Daniel Dumile]] and [[Madlib|Otis Jackson Jr.]], except where noted; all tracks produced by [[Madlib]], except \"The Illest Villains\", produced by Madlib and [[MF Doom|Doom]], and voice skits produced by Doom.<ref name=\"linernotes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Madvillainy|others=Madvillain|year=2004|type=liner notes|publisher=[[Stones Throw Records]]|id=STH2065|location=Los Angeles, California}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| title1          = The Illest Villains \n| length1         = 1:55\n\n| title2          = Accordion \n| length2         = 1:58\n\n| title3          = Meat Grinder\n| length3         = 2:11\n\n| title4          = Bistro\n| length4         = 1:07\n\n| title5          = Raid \n| note5           = featuring [[MED (rapper)|MED]] a.k.a. Medaphoar\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Dumile|Jackson Jr.|[[MED (rapper)|Nick Rodriguez]]}}\n| length5         = 2:30\n\n| title6          = America\u2019s Most Blunted\n| note6           = featuring [[Quasimoto|Lord Quas]]\n| music6          = \n| length6         = 3:54\n\n| title7          = Sickfit\n| note7           = Instrumental\n| writer7         = Jackson Jr.\n| length7         = 1:21\n\n| title8          = Rainbows\n| length8         = 2:51\n\n| title9          = Curls\n| length9         = 1:35\n\n| title10         = Do Not Fire!\n| note10          = Instrumental\n| writer10        = Jackson Jr.\n| length10        = 0:52\n\n| title11         = Money Folder\n| length11        = 3:02\n\n| title12         = Shadows of Tomorrow\n| note12          = featuring Lord Quas\n| length